[Patient] Can you recommend some safe exercises for me to do at home?
[Educator] Walking and light aerobic exercises can be good options for you.
[Patient] What about strength training?
[Educator] Yes, you can do strength training with light weights or resistance bands.
[Patient] Are there any exercises I should avoid?
[Educator] Avoid high-intensity exercises and heavy lifting to protect your heart.
[Patient] How often should I exercise?
[Educator] Aim for at least 30 minutes of exercise most days of the week.
[Patient] Can I still exercise if I feel tired?
[Educator] Listen to your body and rest if you feel too tired to exercise.
[Patient] What if I have trouble breathing during exercise?
[Educator] Stop exercising and rest if you have trouble breathing or chest pain.
[Patient] Should I track my progress?
[Educator] Keeping a log of your exercise can help you stay motivated.
[Patient] Any tips for staying motivated?
[Educator] Find activities you enjoy and exercise with a friend for support.
[Patient] Can I do yoga or Pilates?
[Educator] Yes, yoga and Pilates can be great for improving flexibility and strength.
[Patient] How can I stay safe while exercising in my neighborhood?
[Educator] Try to exercise during daylight hours and avoid isolated areas.
[Patient] Should I warm up before exercising?
[Educator] Yes, a gentle warm-up can help prevent injury and prepare your body.
[Patient] Thank you for all the helpful exercise recommendations!